1
00:00:02,461 --> 00:00:05,214
MAN: Close your eyes
and tell me what you see.

2
00:00:12,054 --> 00:00:13,514
The library.

3
00:00:20,103 --> 00:00:21,772
Open your eyes again.

4
00:00:24,358 --> 00:00:27,444
-Where are you now?
-My living room, Dr Moon.

5
00:00:28,195 --> 00:00:31,448
-When you close your eyes?
-I go to the library.

6
00:00:34,076 --> 00:00:36,286
Go to the library now.

7
00:00:37,788 --> 00:00:40,374
-DR MOON: Are you back there?
-Yes.

8
00:00:41,250 --> 00:00:43,210
The same part?

9
00:00:43,293 --> 00:00:46,964
GIRL: No, it's always different.
The library goes on forever.

10
00:00:48,757 --> 00:00:52,553
-How do you move around?
-By wishing.

11
00:00:54,137 --> 00:00:55,931
(DOOR RATTLING)

12
00:00:57,182 --> 00:00:58,934
-What's wrong?
-Something's here.

13
00:00:59,351 --> 00:01:01,353
Someone's got in.
No one's supposed to get in.

14
00:01:01,436 --> 00:01:03,772
She's never mentioned anyone else.
She's always been alone.

15
00:01:03,855 --> 00:01:05,399
Someone's in my library.

16
00:01:08,318 --> 00:01:10,821
No, no, please! That's not allowed!
It's not allowed!

17
00:01:10,904 --> 00:01:12,406
Listen to me.

18
00:01:13,532 --> 00:01:15,450
The library is in your mind.

19
00:01:15,534 --> 00:01:18,328
I know it's in my mind.
But something's got inside.

20
00:01:30,507 --> 00:01:34,845
Oh, hello!
Sorry to burst in on you like this.

21
00:01:34,928 --> 00:01:36,430
Okay if we stop here for a bit?

22
00:01:38,265 --> 00:01:40,142
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

23
00:02:17,429 --> 00:02:21,600
Books!
People never really stop loving books.

24
00:02:23,852 --> 00:02:25,771
51st century.

25
00:02:25,896 --> 00:02:29,733
By now you've got holovids,
direct-to-brain downloads, fiction-mist.

26
00:02:29,858 --> 00:02:33,737
But you need the smell.
The smell of books, Donna. Deep breath.

27
00:02:38,075 --> 00:02:39,534
The library.

28
00:02:41,745 --> 00:02:45,290
So big it doesn't need a name,
just a great, big "the".

29
00:02:45,415 --> 00:02:49,002
-It's like a city.
-It's a world, literally, a world.

30
00:02:49,086 --> 00:02:51,421
The whole core of the planet
is the index computer,

31
00:02:51,505 --> 00:02:55,217
biggest hard drive ever.
And up here, every book ever written.

32
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:59,680
Whole continents of
Jeffrey Archer, Bridget Jones,

33
00:02:59,763 --> 00:03:02,224
Monty Python's Big Red Book.

34
00:03:02,307 --> 00:03:05,185
Brand-new editions, especially printed.

35
00:03:06,687 --> 00:03:09,106
We're near the equator, so...

36
00:03:11,066 --> 00:03:14,903
This must be biographies!
I love biographies.

37
00:03:14,986 --> 00:03:17,239
Yeah, very you.
Always a death at the end.

38
00:03:17,322 --> 00:03:20,409
You need a good death.
Without death there'd only be comedies.

39
00:03:20,492 --> 00:03:22,119
Dying gives us size.

40
00:03:22,202 --> 00:03:24,830
Whay! Spoilers.

41
00:03:24,913 --> 00:03:27,374
-What?
-These books are from your future.

42
00:03:27,457 --> 00:03:29,543
You don't wanna read ahead,
spoil all the surprises.

43
00:03:29,626 --> 00:03:30,961
It's like peeking at the end.

44
00:03:31,044 --> 00:03:34,297
Isn't travelling with you
one big spoiler?

45
00:03:34,381 --> 00:03:38,176
I try to keep you away
from major plot developments.

46
00:03:39,177 --> 00:03:42,973
Which, to be honest,
I seem to be very bad at

47
00:03:43,098 --> 00:03:47,310
'cause, you know what, this is
the biggest library in the universe.

48
00:03:47,394 --> 00:03:49,479
So where is everyone?

49
00:03:53,900 --> 00:03:57,154
-It's silent.
-The library?

50
00:04:00,741 --> 00:04:02,200
The planet.

51
00:04:04,578 --> 00:04:06,580
The whole planet.

52
00:04:08,165 --> 00:04:09,708
Maybe it's a Sunday.

53
00:04:09,791 --> 00:04:13,628
No, I never land on Sundays.
Sundays are boring.

54
00:04:14,337 --> 00:04:18,925
Oh, maybe everyone's really,
really quiet.

55
00:04:19,009 --> 00:04:20,677
Yeah, maybe.

56
00:04:21,470 --> 00:04:24,181
But they'd still show up on the system.

57
00:04:24,264 --> 00:04:29,352
-Doctor, why are we here? Really, why?
-Oh, you know, just passing.

58
00:04:29,436 --> 00:04:32,439
No, seriously.
It was all, "Let's hit the beach,"

59
00:04:32,522 --> 00:04:35,484
then suddenly we're in a library. Why?

60
00:04:35,567 --> 00:04:38,278
-Now that's interesting.
-What?

61
00:04:38,361 --> 00:04:41,656
Scanning for life forms. If I do a scan
looking for your basic humanoids,

62
00:04:41,740 --> 00:04:44,034
you know, your book-readers,
few limbs and a face,

63
00:04:44,117 --> 00:04:46,453
apart from us, I get nothing.

64
00:04:46,536 --> 00:04:49,790
Zippo, nada. See, nobody home.

65
00:04:50,916 --> 00:04:54,419
But if I widen the parameters
to any kind of life...

66
00:04:58,882 --> 00:05:01,968
A million million. Gives up after that.

67
00:05:04,513 --> 00:05:06,681
A million million.

68
00:05:07,974 --> 00:05:10,894
DONNA: But there's nothing here.
There's no one.

69
00:05:11,937 --> 00:05:14,105
And not a sound.

70
00:05:15,816 --> 00:05:18,401
A million million life forms

71
00:05:19,653 --> 00:05:21,905
and silence in the library.

72
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:25,742
But there's no one here.

73
00:05:25,909 --> 00:05:29,079
There's just books.
I mean, it's not the books, is it?

74
00:05:29,162 --> 00:05:31,164
I mean, it can't be the books, can it?

75
00:05:31,248 --> 00:05:33,625
I mean, books can't be alive.

76
00:05:45,262 --> 00:05:47,472
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Welcome!

77
00:05:49,349 --> 00:05:51,643
-That came from here?
-Yeah.

78
00:06:06,533 --> 00:06:12,372
I am Courtesy Node 710/Aqua.
Please enjoy the library

79
00:06:12,455 --> 00:06:16,585
and respect the personal access codes
of all your fellow readers,

80
00:06:16,668 --> 00:06:20,213
regardless of species or hygiene taboo.

81
00:06:20,297 --> 00:06:24,134
-That face, it looks real.
-Yeah, don't worry about it.

82
00:06:24,217 --> 00:06:26,928
A statue with a real face, though?

83
00:06:27,012 --> 00:06:29,973
-It's a hologram or something, innit?
-No, but really, it's fine.

84
00:06:30,098 --> 00:06:33,810
Additional. There follows
a brief message from the head librarian

85
00:06:33,894 --> 00:06:35,478
for your urgent attention.

86
00:06:35,562 --> 00:06:38,148
It has been edited for tone and content

87
00:06:38,231 --> 00:06:42,319
by a Felman Lux
Automated Decency Filter.

88
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:44,112
Message follows.

89
00:06:44,195 --> 00:06:47,657
Run. For God's sake, run.

90
00:06:47,741 --> 00:06:51,828
Nowhere is safe.
The library has sealed itself.

91
00:06:51,912 --> 00:06:54,706
We can't...Oh, they're here.

92
00:06:55,498 --> 00:06:57,626
Arg. Slarg. Snick.

93
00:06:57,709 --> 00:06:59,711
Message ends.

94
00:06:59,794 --> 00:07:04,966
Please switch off your mobile comm-units
for the comfort of other readers.

95
00:07:05,050 --> 00:07:07,761
So that's why we're here.

96
00:07:07,844 --> 00:07:09,930
Any other messages, same date stamp?

97
00:07:10,013 --> 00:07:12,265
One additional message.

98
00:07:12,349 --> 00:07:16,144
This message carries
a Felman Lux Coherency Warning of...

99
00:07:16,227 --> 00:07:18,939
Yeah, yeah. Fine, fine, fine!
Just play it.

100
00:07:19,022 --> 00:07:21,483
Message follows.

101
00:07:21,566 --> 00:07:22,943
Count the shadows.

102
00:07:23,026 --> 00:07:27,864
For God's sake remember,
if you want to live, count the shadows.

103
00:07:27,948 --> 00:07:29,991
Message ends.

104
00:07:35,538 --> 00:07:38,083
-Donna.
-Yeah.

105
00:07:40,043 --> 00:07:42,170
Stay out of the shadows.

106
00:07:43,713 --> 00:07:46,091
Why, what's in the shadows?

107
00:08:04,734 --> 00:08:08,530
So, we weren't just
in the neighbourhood.

108
00:08:08,613 --> 00:08:12,117
Yeah, I kind of, sort of, lied a bit.

109
00:08:12,242 --> 00:08:14,911
I got a message on the psychic paper.

110
00:08:16,538 --> 00:08:18,957
What do you think? Cry for help?

111
00:08:19,499 --> 00:08:22,377
Cry for help with a kiss?

112
00:08:23,294 --> 00:08:24,921
We've all done that.

113
00:08:25,046 --> 00:08:27,590
-Who's it from?
-No idea.

114
00:08:27,674 --> 00:08:29,676
-So why did we come here? Why did you...
-Donna.

115
00:08:29,759 --> 00:08:32,470
(BEEPING)

116
00:08:33,847 --> 00:08:36,349
-What' s happening?
-Run! |

117
00:08:37,726 --> 00:08:38,810
Come on!

118
00:08:38,893 --> 00:08:42,022
-What, is it locked?
-Jammed! The wood's warped.

119
00:08:42,564 --> 00:08:44,941
Sonic it! Use the thingy!

120
00:08:45,025 --> 00:08:46,693
I can't, it's wood.

121
00:08:46,776 --> 00:08:49,279
-What, it doesn't do wood?
-Hang on, hang on.

122
00:08:49,362 --> 00:08:52,490
I can vibrate the molecules, fry
the bindings, I can shatter line the...

123
00:08:52,574 --> 00:08:53,992
Oh, get out of the way!

124
00:09:03,668 --> 00:09:08,131
Oh, hello!
Sorry to burst in on you like this.

125
00:09:08,298 --> 00:09:09,549
Okay if we stop here for a bit?

126
00:09:12,677 --> 00:09:14,304
What is it?

127
00:09:15,930 --> 00:09:17,348
A security camera.

128
00:09:19,976 --> 00:09:22,020
Switched itself off.

129
00:09:25,106 --> 00:09:28,193
They were in my library.
How can they be in my library?

130
00:09:28,276 --> 00:09:29,611
Who were they?

131
00:09:29,694 --> 00:09:30,779
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

132
00:09:30,862 --> 00:09:33,698
-What's that? What's that noise?
-What noise?

133
00:09:37,118 --> 00:09:40,371
-Nice door skills, Donna.
-Yeah, well, you know, boyfriends.

134
00:09:40,455 --> 00:09:43,124
Sometimes you need
the element of surprise.

135
00:09:43,208 --> 00:09:46,211
What was that? What was after us?

136
00:09:46,294 --> 00:09:49,005
I mean,
did we just run away from a power cut?

137
00:09:49,130 --> 00:09:50,715
Possibly.

138
00:09:52,634 --> 00:09:54,427
Are we safe here?

139
00:09:55,678 --> 00:09:58,264
Of course we're safe.
There's a little shop.

140
00:10:03,603 --> 00:10:04,854
Gotcha!

141
00:10:06,523 --> 00:10:10,819
(SOBBING) No, stop it! No! No!

142
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:17,659
Ooh, I'm sorry. I really am.
I'm sorry, I'm so sorry.

143
00:10:18,701 --> 00:10:19,869
It's alive.

144
00:10:19,994 --> 00:10:22,622
You said it was a security camera.

145
00:10:22,705 --> 00:10:25,875
It is. It's an alive one.

146
00:10:26,668 --> 00:10:28,878
DR MOON: Can you hear me?

147
00:10:29,003 --> 00:10:30,713
Are you all right?

148
00:10:33,675 --> 00:10:37,804
-Others are coming.
-Who's coming? Who are the others?

149
00:10:37,887 --> 00:10:40,807
The library is breached.
Others are coming.

150
00:10:40,890 --> 00:10:42,142
What others?

151
00:10:42,725 --> 00:10:45,812
DONNA: "Others"? What's it mean, others?

152
00:10:50,066 --> 00:10:52,402
Excuse me. What does it mean, others?

153
00:10:52,485 --> 00:10:55,655
That's barely more than a speak
your weight machine. It can't help you.

154
00:10:55,738 --> 00:10:57,991
So why's it got a face?

155
00:10:58,074 --> 00:11:00,869
This flesh aspect was donated
by Mark Chambers

156
00:11:00,952 --> 00:11:02,954
on the occasion of his death.

157
00:11:04,122 --> 00:11:05,665
It's a real face.

158
00:11:05,748 --> 00:11:08,459
It has been actualised
individually for you

159
00:11:08,543 --> 00:11:13,047
from the many facial aspects
saved to our extensive flesh banks.

160
00:11:13,423 --> 00:11:15,508
Please enjoy.

161
00:11:15,592 --> 00:11:18,469
It chose me a dead face
it thought I'd like?

162
00:11:18,553 --> 00:11:20,680
That statue's got
a real dead person's face on it!

163
00:11:20,763 --> 00:11:24,851
It's the 51st century. That's basically
like donating a park bench.

164
00:11:24,934 --> 00:11:27,228
It's donating a face!

165
00:11:27,312 --> 00:11:30,273
-No! Wait! No!
-Hands!

166
00:11:30,356 --> 00:11:32,108
Shadow, look.

167
00:11:33,610 --> 00:11:35,236
What about it?

168
00:11:35,320 --> 00:11:37,906
DOCTOR: Count the shadows.

169
00:11:37,989 --> 00:11:41,701
One, there. I've counted it, one shadow.

170
00:11:41,784 --> 00:11:43,286
Yeah.

171
00:11:44,454 --> 00:11:46,456
But what's casting it?

172
00:11:56,132 --> 00:11:59,594
Oh! I'm thick! Look at me!
I'm old and thick!

173
00:11:59,677 --> 00:12:02,639
Head's too full of stuff!
I need a bigger head!

174
00:12:07,143 --> 00:12:08,728
DONNA: Power must be going.

175
00:12:08,811 --> 00:12:12,065
This place runs on fission cells.
They'll out-burn the sun.

176
00:12:12,148 --> 00:12:14,776
-Then why is it dark?
-It's not dark.

177
00:12:19,239 --> 00:12:22,075
That shadow, it's gone.

178
00:12:23,243 --> 00:12:25,578
-We need to get back to the Tardis.
-Why?

179
00:12:25,662 --> 00:12:28,456
Because that shadow hasn't gone,
it's moved.

180
00:12:29,415 --> 00:12:32,794
Reminder. The library has been breached.
Others are coming.

181
00:12:33,419 --> 00:12:37,006
Reminder. The library has been breached.
Others are coming.

182
00:12:37,840 --> 00:12:40,551
Reminder. The library has been breached.
Others are coming.

183
00:12:46,516 --> 00:12:50,353
Reminder. The library has been breached.
Others are coming.

184
00:12:51,521 --> 00:12:55,024
Reminder. The library has been breached.
Others are coming.

185
00:13:02,615 --> 00:13:04,909
-Hello, sweetie.
-Get out.

186
00:13:05,034 --> 00:13:06,160
Doctor...

187
00:13:06,244 --> 00:13:09,080
All of you, turn around,
get back in your rocket and fly away.

188
00:13:09,163 --> 00:13:11,165
Tell your grandchildren
you came to the library and lived.

189
00:13:11,249 --> 00:13:12,375
They won't believe you.

190
00:13:12,458 --> 00:13:15,586
Pop your helmets, everyone,
we got breathers.

191
00:13:15,670 --> 00:13:18,089
How do you know they're not androids?

192
00:13:18,172 --> 00:13:20,800
'Cause I've dated androids.
They're rubbish.

193
00:13:20,883 --> 00:13:21,926
Who is this?

194
00:13:22,051 --> 00:13:25,096
You said we were the only expedition.
I paid for exclusives.

195
00:13:25,221 --> 00:13:28,224
I lied. I'm always lying.
Bound to be others.

196
00:13:28,349 --> 00:13:30,768
Miss Evangelista,
I want to see the contracts.

197
00:13:30,893 --> 00:13:33,062
You came through the north door?
How was that? Much damage?

198
00:13:33,146 --> 00:13:35,481
Please just leave.
I'm asking you seriously and properly.

199
00:13:35,565 --> 00:13:37,859
Just...Hang on. Did you say expedition?

200
00:13:37,984 --> 00:13:40,862
My expedition. I funded it.

201
00:13:40,945 --> 00:13:44,949
Oh, you're not, are you?
Tell me you're not archaeologists.

202
00:13:45,033 --> 00:13:46,617
Got a problem with archaeologists?

203
00:13:46,701 --> 00:13:49,537
I'm a time traveller.
I point and laugh at archaeologists.

204
00:13:49,620 --> 00:13:52,123
Ah. Professor River Song.

205
00:13:52,248 --> 00:13:54,459
-Archaeologist.
-River Song. Lovely name.

206
00:13:54,584 --> 00:13:56,127
As you're leaving,
and you're leaving now,

207
00:13:56,252 --> 00:13:58,671
you need to set up a quarantine beacon,
code-wall the planet.

208
00:13:58,755 --> 00:14:01,424
The whole planet!
Nobody comes here, not ever again!

209
00:14:01,549 --> 00:14:03,593
Not one living thing,
not here, not ever!

210
00:14:03,676 --> 00:14:06,304
-Stop right there! What's your name?
-Anita.

211
00:14:06,429 --> 00:14:09,599
Anita, stay out of the shadows.
Not a foot, not a finger in the shadows

212
00:14:09,724 --> 00:14:13,436
till you're safely back in your ship.
Goes for all of you, stay in the light!

213
00:14:13,519 --> 00:14:16,272
Find a nice bright spot and just stand.

214
00:14:16,397 --> 00:14:19,609
If you understand me,
look very, very scared.

215
00:14:24,947 --> 00:14:27,450
No, a bit more scared than that.

216
00:14:30,203 --> 00:14:33,164
-Okay, do for now. You, who are you?
-Dave.

217
00:14:33,247 --> 00:14:34,957
-Okay, Dave...
-Oh, well, Other Dave.

218
00:14:35,083 --> 00:14:40,004
Because that's Proper Dave, the pilot.
He was the first Dave. So when...

219
00:14:40,129 --> 00:14:43,049
Other Dave, the way you came,
does it look the same as before?

220
00:14:43,132 --> 00:14:45,968
-Yeah. Oh! It's a bit darker.
-How much darker?

221
00:14:46,052 --> 00:14:49,138
Like, I could see where we came through
just a moment ago. I can't now.

222
00:14:49,222 --> 00:14:50,723
Seal up this door.
We'll find another way out.

223
00:14:50,807 --> 00:14:53,226
-Would you...
-We're not looking for a way out.

224
00:14:53,309 --> 00:14:54,769
Miss Evangelista.

225
00:14:54,852 --> 00:14:59,982
I'm Mr Lux's personal everything.
You need to sign these contracts

226
00:15:00,066 --> 00:15:02,735
agreeing that your individual
experience inside the library

227
00:15:02,819 --> 00:15:06,823
are the intellectual property
of the Felman Lux Corporation.

228
00:15:06,906 --> 00:15:09,242
-Right. Give it here.
-Yeah, lovely. Thanks.

229
00:15:12,912 --> 00:15:15,415
My family built this library.
I have rights.

230
00:15:15,498 --> 00:15:19,001
You have a mouth that won't stop.
You think there's danger here?

231
00:15:19,127 --> 00:15:21,671
Something came to this library
and killed everything in it.

232
00:15:21,796 --> 00:15:24,674
Killed a whole world. Danger? Could be.

233
00:15:24,757 --> 00:15:27,427
That was 100 years ago.
The library's been silent for 100 years.

234
00:15:27,510 --> 00:15:29,679
Whatever came here is long dead.

235
00:15:29,804 --> 00:15:31,848
Bet your life?

236
00:15:31,973 --> 00:15:34,100
Always.

237
00:15:34,183 --> 00:15:37,562
-LUX: What are you doing?
-He said seal the door.

238
00:15:37,687 --> 00:15:39,439
-Torch.
-You're taking orders from him?

239
00:15:39,522 --> 00:15:41,524
Spooky, isn't it?

240
00:15:50,616 --> 00:15:55,246
Almost every species in the universe
has an irrational fear of the dark.

241
00:15:55,371 --> 00:15:58,833
But they're wrong,
'cause it's not irrational.

242
00:16:01,043 --> 00:16:03,588
It's Vashta Nerada.

243
00:16:03,671 --> 00:16:05,631
DONNA: What's Vashta Nerada?

244
00:16:05,715 --> 00:16:08,050
It's what's in the dark.

245
00:16:08,801 --> 00:16:11,179
It's what's always in the dark.

246
00:16:12,346 --> 00:16:14,640
Lights! That's what we need! Lights!
You got lights?

247
00:16:14,724 --> 00:16:15,975
-What for?
-Form a circle,

248
00:16:16,058 --> 00:16:18,478
safe area, big as you can.
Lights pointing out.

249
00:16:18,561 --> 00:16:20,396
-Why?
-Do as he says.

250
00:16:20,480 --> 00:16:22,857
-You're not listening to this man?
-Apparently I am.

251
00:16:22,940 --> 00:16:24,317
Anita, un-pack the lights.

252
00:16:24,400 --> 00:16:27,153
Other Dave, make sure the door's secure
then help Anita.

253
00:16:27,236 --> 00:16:30,281
Mr Lux, put your helmet back on
and block the visor.

254
00:16:30,406 --> 00:16:33,159
Proper Dave, find an active terminal,
access the library database.

255
00:16:33,242 --> 00:16:35,703
See what you can find out about
what happened here 100 years ago.

256
00:16:35,786 --> 00:16:40,166
Pretty boy, you're with me.
Step into my office.

257
00:16:40,249 --> 00:16:44,045
Professor Song,
why am I the only one wearing my helmet?

258
00:16:44,128 --> 00:16:46,047
I don't fancy you.

259
00:16:47,089 --> 00:16:49,342
Probably I can help you.

260
00:16:49,425 --> 00:16:51,802
Pretty boy, with me I said.

261
00:16:55,264 --> 00:16:57,308
-Oh, I , I'm pretty boy?
-Yes! ”

262
00:16:57,391 --> 00:16:59,852
Ooh, that came out a bit quick.

263
00:16:59,977 --> 00:17:01,229
Pretty?

264
00:17:01,312 --> 00:17:02,605
(EXCLAIMS)

265
00:17:03,898 --> 00:17:06,859
Don't let your shadows cross.
Seriously, don't even let them touch.

266
00:17:06,943 --> 00:17:10,321
-Any of them could be infected.
-How could a shadow be infected?

267
00:17:10,446 --> 00:17:13,866
-Excuse me. Can I help?
-No, we're fine.

268
00:17:13,950 --> 00:17:17,954
-I could just, you know, hold things.
-No, really, we're okay.

269
00:17:18,079 --> 00:17:19,830
Okay.

270
00:17:25,795 --> 00:17:27,380
Couldn't she help?

271
00:17:27,463 --> 00:17:30,675
Trust me. I just spent four days
on a ship with that woman. She's a...

272
00:17:30,800 --> 00:17:33,553
Couldn't tell the difference
between the escape pod and the bathroom.

273
00:17:33,636 --> 00:17:36,305
We had to go back for her.

274
00:17:36,389 --> 00:17:37,932
Twice.

275
00:17:39,684 --> 00:17:42,311
(CHATTERING)

276
00:17:48,651 --> 00:17:50,236
(DOCTOR CLEARS THROAT)

277
00:17:50,319 --> 00:17:51,571
Thanks.

278
00:17:51,654 --> 00:17:54,365
-For what?
-The usual, for coming when I call.

279
00:17:54,448 --> 00:17:55,825
Oh, that was you?

280
00:17:55,908 --> 00:17:58,119
You're doing a very good job
acting like you don't know me.

281
00:17:58,202 --> 00:18:01,163
-I'm assuming there's a reason.
-A fairly good one, actually.

282
00:18:01,289 --> 00:18:05,042
Okay, shall we do diaries, then?
Where are we this time?

283
00:18:05,167 --> 00:18:08,087
Ah, going by your face,
I'd say it's early days for you.

284
00:18:08,170 --> 00:18:12,842
Yeah, so, crash of the Byzantium,
have we done that yet?

285
00:18:15,177 --> 00:18:18,347
Obviously ringing no bells.

286
00:18:19,181 --> 00:18:25,187
All right, Oh...Picnic at Asgard.
Have we done Asgard yet?

287
00:18:28,190 --> 00:18:32,028
Obviously not.
Blimey. Very early days, then.

288
00:18:32,111 --> 00:18:36,365
Oh! Life of a time traveller,
never knew it could be such hard work.

289
00:18:36,449 --> 00:18:38,200
Um...

290
00:18:41,829 --> 00:18:43,289
Look at you.

291
00:18:45,541 --> 00:18:48,753
-You're young.
-I'm really not, you know.

292
00:18:48,878 --> 00:18:50,796
Oh, but you are.

293
00:18:52,048 --> 00:18:56,802
Your eyes.
You're younger than I've ever seen you.

294
00:18:59,221 --> 00:19:01,474
You've seen me before, then?

295
00:19:04,477 --> 00:19:05,686
Doctor...

296
00:19:07,188 --> 00:19:09,690
please tell me you know who I am.

297
00:19:11,400 --> 00:19:12,985
Who are you?

298
00:19:18,574 --> 00:19:20,743
(ALARM BUZZING)

299
00:19:22,119 --> 00:19:23,579
PROPER DAVE: Sorry, that was me.

300
00:19:23,663 --> 00:19:25,790
Trying to get through
into the security protocols,

301
00:19:25,873 --> 00:19:29,669
I seem to have set something off.
What is that? Is that an alarm?

302
00:19:29,752 --> 00:19:34,507
-Doctor...Doctor that sounds like...
-Yeah, it is. It's a phone.

303
00:19:34,590 --> 00:19:36,926
(RINGING)

304
00:19:53,067 --> 00:19:55,319
-Dad.
-In a minute.

305
00:20:02,535 --> 00:20:04,203
I'm trying to call up the data core

306
00:20:04,286 --> 00:20:06,163
but it's not responding,
just that noise.

307
00:20:06,288 --> 00:20:09,375
-But it's a phone.
-Let me try something.

308
00:20:13,212 --> 00:20:16,424
Dad, the phone.
Aren't you going to answer it?

309
00:20:17,591 --> 00:20:19,802
It's not ringing, sweetie.

310
00:20:32,481 --> 00:20:35,192
Okay, it don't like that.
Let's try something else.

311
00:20:47,455 --> 00:20:49,874
DOCTOR ON TV: Okay, here it comes.

312
00:20:52,960 --> 00:20:55,087
-Hello.
-Hello.

313
00:20:55,171 --> 00:20:57,590
Are you in my television?

314
00:20:57,673 --> 00:21:02,261
Well no, I'm...I'm sort of in space.

315
00:21:02,344 --> 00:21:04,680
Um, I was trying to
call up the data core

316
00:21:04,764 --> 00:21:07,349
of a Triple-Grid Security Processor.

317
00:21:07,475 --> 00:21:10,603
Would you like to speak to my dad?

318
00:21:10,686 --> 00:21:13,522
Your dad or your mum,
that would be lovely.

319
00:21:14,982 --> 00:21:18,194
I know you. You were in my library.

320
00:21:18,277 --> 00:21:19,820
Your library?

321
00:21:19,904 --> 00:21:21,989
The library's never been
on television before.

322
00:21:22,072 --> 00:21:24,325
What have you done?

323
00:21:24,408 --> 00:21:26,702
Ah, well, um, I just...

324
00:21:31,040 --> 00:21:32,917
What happened? Who was that?

325
00:21:45,346 --> 00:21:47,890
Keep working on those lights.
I need those lights.

326
00:21:47,973 --> 00:21:50,893
You heard him, people.
Let there be light.

327
00:22:06,742 --> 00:22:09,161
Sorry, you're not allowed
to see inside the book.

328
00:22:09,245 --> 00:22:11,956
-It's against the rules.
-What rules?

329
00:22:12,581 --> 00:22:14,041
Your rules.

330
00:22:25,511 --> 00:22:28,430
(CHATTERING ON TELEVISION)

331
00:22:43,279 --> 00:22:44,780
What's that?

332
00:22:46,991 --> 00:22:50,077
-I didn't do that. Did you do that?
-Not me.

333
00:22:53,247 --> 00:22:54,707
What's CAL?

334
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:16,645
You all right?

335
00:23:16,729 --> 00:23:21,233
-What's that? What's happening?
-I don't know.

336
00:23:21,317 --> 00:23:25,446
Oh, thanks for, you know,
offering to help with the lights.

337
00:23:26,447 --> 00:23:30,868
They don't want me.
They think I'm stupid 'cause I'm pretty.

338
00:23:30,993 --> 00:23:33,829
Of course they don't.
Nobody thinks that.

339
00:23:33,954 --> 00:23:37,625
No, they're right, though.
I'm a moron really.

340
00:23:37,708 --> 00:23:41,253
My dad said I had the IQ of plankton
and I was pleased.

341
00:23:41,337 --> 00:23:44,423
(LAUGHING) See, that's funny.

342
00:23:46,425 --> 00:23:48,928
No, I really was pleased.

343
00:23:50,179 --> 00:23:52,640
-Is that funny?
-No. No.

344
00:23:56,018 --> 00:23:59,104
What's causing that?
Is it the little girl?

345
00:23:59,188 --> 00:24:02,274
Who is the little girl?
What's she gotta do with this place?

346
00:24:02,858 --> 00:24:07,613
ON TV: No way. No swapsies.
This eeny-weeny bit of metal is...

347
00:24:07,905 --> 00:24:11,200
How does the data core work?
What's the principle? What's CAL?

348
00:24:11,283 --> 00:24:12,952
Ask Mr Lux.

349
00:24:13,661 --> 00:24:14,954
CAL, what is it?

350
00:24:15,037 --> 00:24:19,249
Sorry, you didn't sign
your personal experience contracts.

351
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:21,460
Mr Lux, right now

352
00:24:21,543 --> 00:24:25,923
you're in more danger than
you've ever been in your whole life.

353
00:24:26,006 --> 00:24:30,511
-And you're protecting a patent?
-I'm protecting my family's pride.

354
00:24:30,844 --> 00:24:33,138
Well, funny thing, Mr Lux.

355
00:24:33,222 --> 00:24:35,891
I don't wanna see
everyone in this room dead

356
00:24:35,975 --> 00:24:39,395
because some idiot thinks his pride
is more important.

357
00:24:41,563 --> 00:24:44,400
Then why don't you sign his contract?

358
00:24:47,194 --> 00:24:50,239
I didn't either.
I'm getting worse than you.

359
00:24:51,782 --> 00:24:55,828
Okay. Okay, let's start at
the beginning. What happened here?

360
00:24:55,911 --> 00:24:58,747
On the actual day, 100 years ago,
what physically happened?

361
00:24:58,956 --> 00:25:01,709
MAN ON TV: See? How about this huge...

362
00:25:02,876 --> 00:25:06,547
SONG: There was a message
from the library, just one.

363
00:25:06,630 --> 00:25:10,426
"The lights are going out.”
Then the computer sealed the planet,

364
00:25:10,509 --> 00:25:12,970
and there was nothing for 100 years.

365
00:25:13,053 --> 00:25:14,847
It's taken three generations
of my family

366
00:25:14,930 --> 00:25:16,765
just to decode the seals
and get back in.

367
00:25:16,932 --> 00:25:21,145
-Um, excuse me?
-LUX: Not just now.

368
00:25:22,271 --> 00:25:24,982
There was one other thing
in the last message.

369
00:25:25,274 --> 00:25:27,818
-That's confidential.
-I trust this man.

370
00:25:27,901 --> 00:25:30,029
With my life, with everything.

371
00:25:30,112 --> 00:25:32,990
-You've only just met him.
-No. He's only just met me.

372
00:25:36,118 --> 00:25:39,621
-Um, this might be important, actually.
-In a moment.

373
00:25:42,332 --> 00:25:45,878
This is a data extract
that came with the message.

374
00:25:45,961 --> 00:25:49,631
"4,022 saved. No survivors."

375
00:25:51,467 --> 00:25:53,552
4,022, that's the exact number of people

376
00:25:53,635 --> 00:25:56,847
who were in the library
when the planet was sealed.

377
00:25:56,930 --> 00:26:00,893
How can 4,022 people have been saved
if there were no survivors?

378
00:26:00,976 --> 00:26:02,895
That's what we're here to find out.

379
00:26:02,978 --> 00:26:06,565
And so far,
what we haven't found are any bodies.

380
00:26:50,818 --> 00:26:52,694
(DISTANT RUMBLING)

381
00:27:14,383 --> 00:27:16,385
(EVANGELISTA SCREAMS)

382
00:27:29,064 --> 00:27:31,024
Everybody, careful. Stay in the light.

383
00:27:31,108 --> 00:27:32,734
You keep saying that,
I don't see the point.

384
00:27:32,818 --> 00:27:34,611
-Who screamed?
-Miss Evangelista.

385
00:27:34,736 --> 00:27:36,238
Where is she?

386
00:27:37,322 --> 00:27:39,783
Miss Evangelista,
please state your current...

387
00:27:39,867 --> 00:27:41,535
(ECHOING)

388
00:27:45,455 --> 00:27:47,332
Please state your current...

389
00:27:47,416 --> 00:27:49,626
(ECHOING)

390
00:27:49,710 --> 00:27:51,086
...position.

391
00:28:02,055 --> 00:28:03,432
It's her.

392
00:28:07,936 --> 00:28:09,563
That's Miss Evangelista.

393
00:28:09,646 --> 00:28:11,857
We heard her scream a few seconds ago.

394
00:28:11,940 --> 00:28:14,026
What could do that to a person
in a few seconds?

395
00:28:14,109 --> 00:28:16,695
-Took a lot less than a few seconds.
-What did?

396
00:28:16,778 --> 00:28:20,032
-EVANGELISTA: Hello?
-Uh, I'm sorry, everyone.

397
00:28:21,241 --> 00:28:23,660
This isn't going to be pleasant.

398
00:28:24,286 --> 00:28:26,496
-She's ghosting.
-She's what?

399
00:28:27,706 --> 00:28:29,958
Hello, excuse me?

400
00:28:31,043 --> 00:28:34,338
I'm sorry, hello, excuse me?

401
00:28:34,421 --> 00:28:37,758
That's...That's her.
That's Miss Evangelista.

402
00:28:37,841 --> 00:28:40,802
I don't wanna sound horrible,
but couldn't we just, you know...

403
00:28:40,886 --> 00:28:45,140
This is her last moment, no, we can't.
A little respect, thank you.

404
00:28:45,224 --> 00:28:48,393
Sorry, where am I? Excuse me?

405
00:28:48,477 --> 00:28:52,397
-But that's Miss Evangelista.
-It's a data ghost.

406
00:28:52,481 --> 00:28:55,192
She'll be gone in a moment.

407
00:28:55,317 --> 00:28:59,029
(ECHOING) Miss Evangelista, you're fine.
Just relax.

408
00:28:59,112 --> 00:29:01,240
We'll be with you presently.

409
00:29:01,323 --> 00:29:03,325
What's a data ghost?

410
00:29:03,408 --> 00:29:05,535
There's a neural relay
in the communicator,

411
00:29:05,619 --> 00:29:07,162
lets you send thought-mails.

412
00:29:07,246 --> 00:29:10,624
That's it there. Those green lights.

413
00:29:10,707 --> 00:29:13,585
Sometimes it can hold an impression
of a living consciousness

414
00:29:13,669 --> 00:29:15,963
for a short time after death.

415
00:29:16,630 --> 00:29:18,548
Like an after image.

416
00:29:19,466 --> 00:29:21,843
Her grandfather lasted a day.

417
00:29:22,803 --> 00:29:25,722
Kept talking about his shoelaces.

418
00:29:27,391 --> 00:29:28,850
She's in there.

419
00:29:28,934 --> 00:29:32,521
I can't see. I can't... Where am I?

420
00:29:32,688 --> 00:29:36,358
She's just brainwaves now.
Pattern won't hold for long.

421
00:29:37,734 --> 00:29:39,695
She's conscious.

422
00:29:39,778 --> 00:29:42,906
-She's thinking.
-I can't see. I can't...

423
00:29:42,990 --> 00:29:47,369
-I don't know what I'm thinking.
-She's a footprint on the beach.

424
00:29:47,452 --> 00:29:50,622
-And the tide's coming in.
-Where is that woman?

425
00:29:51,581 --> 00:29:54,084
The nice woman, is she there?

426
00:29:55,043 --> 00:29:56,503
What woman?

427
00:29:57,713 --> 00:29:59,464
She means...

428
00:30:00,173 --> 00:30:02,759
I think she means me.

429
00:30:02,884 --> 00:30:06,096
Is she there? The nice woman?

430
00:30:06,513 --> 00:30:09,766
Yes, she's here. Hang on.

431
00:30:11,518 --> 00:30:13,437
Go ahead, she can hear you.

432
00:30:13,520 --> 00:30:15,439
Hello, are you there?

433
00:30:16,523 --> 00:30:17,816
Help her.

434
00:30:18,400 --> 00:30:21,028
-She's dead.
-Yeah, help her.

435
00:30:22,195 --> 00:30:25,866
Hello, is that the nice woman?

436
00:30:26,241 --> 00:30:31,872
Yeah. Hello. Yeah, I'm...I'm here.
You okay?

437
00:30:33,290 --> 00:30:37,127
What I said before, about being stupid,

438
00:30:37,210 --> 00:30:39,379
don't tell the others,
they'll only laugh.

439
00:30:39,463 --> 00:30:42,257
Of course I won't.
Course I won't tell them.

440
00:30:42,341 --> 00:30:45,469
Don't tell the others,
they'll only laugh.

441
00:30:45,552 --> 00:30:49,222
I won't tell them. I said I won't.

442
00:30:49,306 --> 00:30:52,267
Don't tell the others,
they'll only laugh.

443
00:30:53,477 --> 00:30:55,228
I'm not going to tell them.

444
00:30:55,312 --> 00:30:56,396
Don't tell the others,
they'll only laugh.

445
00:30:56,480 --> 00:30:58,648
She's looping now.
The pattern's degrading.

446
00:30:58,732 --> 00:31:01,026
I can't think...

447
00:31:01,109 --> 00:31:04,154
(SIGNAL FLUTTERING) I don't know...I...

448
00:31:04,237 --> 00:31:06,948
. __7__.

449
00:31:07,616 --> 00:31:11,244
Ice cream. Ice cream.

450
00:31:11,328 --> 00:31:15,374
Ice cream. Ice cream. Ice cream...

451
00:31:15,916 --> 00:31:18,460
-Does anybody mind if I...
-Ice cream...

452
00:31:18,627 --> 00:31:23,256
Ice cream. Ice cream. Ice cream...

453
00:31:27,094 --> 00:31:30,764
That was... That was horrible.

454
00:31:30,847 --> 00:31:34,643
That was the most horrible thing
I've ever seen.

455
00:31:34,768 --> 00:31:38,438
Well, it's just a freak of technology.

456
00:31:40,649 --> 00:31:45,570
Whatever did this to her,
whatever killed her,

457
00:31:45,654 --> 00:31:48,490
-I'd like a word with that.
-I'll introduce you.

458
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:02,087
-I'm gonna need a packed lunch.
-Hang on.

459
00:32:04,297 --> 00:32:07,342
-What's in that book?
-Spoilers.

460
00:32:07,426 --> 00:32:09,386
Who are you?

461
00:32:09,469 --> 00:32:11,930
-Professor River Song. University of...
-To me.

462
00:32:12,013 --> 00:32:14,474
-Who are you to me?
-Again.

463
00:32:14,558 --> 00:32:16,017
Spoilers.

464
00:32:17,060 --> 00:32:20,230
Chicken and a bit of salad,
knock yourself out.

465
00:32:23,650 --> 00:32:27,571
Right, you lot.
Let's all meet the Vashta Nerada.

466
00:32:33,201 --> 00:32:36,538
Darling, Dr Moon is going now,
but he'd like a word with you alone.

467
00:32:36,663 --> 00:32:39,708
-Is that all right?
-Yes, of course, Dr Moon.

468
00:32:39,833 --> 00:32:41,334
Thank you.

469
00:32:45,046 --> 00:32:47,799
Now, listen.

470
00:32:50,218 --> 00:32:52,387
This is important.

471
00:32:52,471 --> 00:32:56,850
There's the real world,
and there's the world of nightmares.

472
00:32:56,933 --> 00:32:58,894
That's right, isn't it?
You understand that?

473
00:32:58,977 --> 00:33:00,937
Yes, I know, Dr Moon.

474
00:33:02,189 --> 00:33:06,193
What I want you to remember is this,
and I know it's hard.

475
00:33:07,152 --> 00:33:12,616
The real world is a lie,
and your nightmares are real.

476
00:33:13,241 --> 00:33:16,995
The library is real.
There are people trapped in there.

477
00:33:17,078 --> 00:33:20,248
People who need to be saved.

478
00:33:20,332 --> 00:33:25,670
The shadows are moving again.
Those people are depending on you.

479
00:33:26,630 --> 00:33:30,258
Only you can save them. Only you.

480
00:33:39,434 --> 00:33:44,105
You travel with him, don't you?
The Doctor, you travel with him.

481
00:33:45,106 --> 00:33:46,650
What of it?

482
00:33:46,775 --> 00:33:49,110
-Proper Dave, could you move over a bit?
-Why?

483
00:33:49,194 --> 00:33:51,780
Over there by the water cooler. Thanks.

484
00:33:55,033 --> 00:33:59,371
DONNA: You know him, don't you?
SONG: Oh, God, do I know that man!

485
00:33:59,913 --> 00:34:02,749
We go way back, that man and me.

486
00:34:02,832 --> 00:34:05,460
-Just not this far back.
-I'm sorry, what?

487
00:34:06,795 --> 00:34:08,838
He hasn't met me yet.

488
00:34:10,966 --> 00:34:15,178
I sent him a message, but it went wrong.
It arrived too early.

489
00:34:15,303 --> 00:34:18,890
This is the Doctor in the days
before he knew me.

490
00:34:20,684 --> 00:34:23,144
And he looks at me...

491
00:34:23,812 --> 00:34:27,357
He looks right through me
and it shouldn't kill me but it does.

492
00:34:27,482 --> 00:34:30,402
What're you talking about?
Are you just talking rubbish?

493
00:34:30,485 --> 00:34:32,445
Do you know him, or don't you?

494
00:34:32,529 --> 00:34:36,074
-DOCTOR: Donna! Quiet, I'm working.
-Sorry.

495
00:34:36,157 --> 00:34:40,954
-Donna, you're Donna? Donna Noble.
-Yeah. Why?

496
00:34:42,497 --> 00:34:46,293
I do know the Doctor. But in the future.

497
00:34:47,252 --> 00:34:49,713
His personal future.

498
00:34:49,796 --> 00:34:53,508
So, why don't you know me?
Where am I in the future?

499
00:34:56,511 --> 00:34:59,014
DOCTOR: Okay, got a live one.

500
00:35:00,515 --> 00:35:05,186
That's not darkness down those tunnels.
This is not a shadow.

501
00:35:05,270 --> 00:35:08,732
It's a swarm. A man-eating swarm.

502
00:35:12,694 --> 00:35:16,698
The piranhas of the air,
the Vashta Nerada.

503
00:35:16,823 --> 00:35:19,868
Literally, the shadows
that melt the flesh.

504
00:35:19,993 --> 00:35:23,121
Most planets have them,
but usually in small clusters.

505
00:35:23,330 --> 00:35:26,750
I've never seen an infestation
on this scale, or this aggressive.

506
00:35:26,875 --> 00:35:28,793
What do you mean, most planets?
Not Earth?

507
00:35:28,877 --> 00:35:32,047
Mmm. Earth, and a billion other worlds.

508
00:35:32,172 --> 00:35:34,257
Where there's meat,
there's Vashta Nerada.

509
00:35:34,382 --> 00:35:37,260
You can see them sometimes, if you look.

510
00:35:37,385 --> 00:35:39,554
The dust in sunbeams.

511
00:35:40,722 --> 00:35:43,183
If they were on Earth, we'd know.

512
00:35:43,308 --> 00:35:46,269
Nah. Normally they live on road-kill.

513
00:35:46,394 --> 00:35:49,064
But sometimes people go missing.

514
00:35:49,648 --> 00:35:52,400
Not everyone comes back out of the dark.

515
00:35:52,484 --> 00:35:56,613
-Every shadow?
-No, but any shadow.

516
00:35:57,238 --> 00:35:58,907
So, what do we do?

517
00:35:59,032 --> 00:36:03,161
Daleks, aim for the eye-stalk.
Sontarans, back of the neck.

518
00:36:03,244 --> 00:36:05,580
Vashta Nerada...

519
00:36:06,122 --> 00:36:08,416
run. Just run.

520
00:36:08,541 --> 00:36:10,001
Run? Run where?

521
00:36:10,085 --> 00:36:12,504
This is an index point, there must be
an exit teleport somewhere.

522
00:36:12,629 --> 00:36:14,422
Don't look at me,
I haven't memorised the schematics.

523
00:36:15,006 --> 00:36:18,551
Doctor, the little shop. They always
make you go through the little shop

524
00:36:18,635 --> 00:36:21,680
on the way out
so they can sell you stuff.

525
00:36:21,763 --> 00:36:24,182
You're right. Brilliant!
That's why I like the little shop.

526
00:36:24,265 --> 00:36:26,810
-Okay, let's move it.
-Actually, Proper Dave...

527
00:36:26,935 --> 00:36:28,395
Could you stay
where you are for a moment?

528
00:36:28,478 --> 00:36:30,188
Why?

529
00:36:31,106 --> 00:36:34,067
I'm sorry. I'm so, so sorry.

530
00:36:36,986 --> 00:36:39,739
But you've got two shadows.

531
00:36:45,620 --> 00:36:50,291
It's how they hunt. They latch onto
a food source and keep it fresh.

532
00:36:52,419 --> 00:36:54,379
-What do I do?
-You stay absolutely still.

533
00:36:54,462 --> 00:36:57,006
Like there's a wasp in the room.
Like there's a million wasps.

534
00:36:57,132 --> 00:36:59,134
-We're not leaving you, Dave.
-Of course we're not leaving you.

535
00:36:59,259 --> 00:37:01,886
Where's your helmet?
Don't point, just tell me.

536
00:37:01,970 --> 00:37:04,222
On the floor, by my bag.

537
00:37:04,305 --> 00:37:06,433
Don't cross his shadow!

538
00:37:13,106 --> 00:37:16,234
Thanks. Now, the rest of you,

539
00:37:16,317 --> 00:37:19,279
helmets back on and sealed up.
We'll need everything we've got.

540
00:37:19,404 --> 00:37:21,072
DONNA: Doctor, we haven't got
any helmets.

541
00:37:21,156 --> 00:37:23,825
-Yeah, but we're safe anyway.
-How are we safe?

542
00:37:23,908 --> 00:37:25,577
We're not.
That was a clever lie to shut you up.

543
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:27,579
Professor, anything I can do
with the suit?

544
00:37:27,662 --> 00:37:28,872
What good are the damn suits?

545
00:37:28,955 --> 00:37:31,374
Miss Evangelista was wearing a suit,
there was nothing left.

546
00:37:31,458 --> 00:37:33,960
We can increase the mesh density.
Dial it up 400%.

547
00:37:34,085 --> 00:37:36,421
-Make it a tougher meal.
-DOCTOR: Okay.

548
00:37:38,298 --> 00:37:40,467
-800%. Pass it on.
-Gotcha.

549
00:37:40,884 --> 00:37:43,136
-What's that?
-It's a screwdriver.

550
00:37:44,429 --> 00:37:47,015
-It's sonic.
-Yeah, I know. Snap.

551
00:37:54,689 --> 00:37:56,316
With me, come on.

552
00:38:00,695 --> 00:38:02,781
What are we doing? We're shopping?
Is it a good time to shop?

553
00:38:02,864 --> 00:38:05,366
No talking, just moving. Try it.
Right, stand out in the middle.

554
00:38:05,450 --> 00:38:06,993
It's a teleport. Stand in the middle.

555
00:38:07,076 --> 00:38:08,703
Can't send the others,
Tardis won't recognise them.

556
00:38:08,787 --> 00:38:11,122
-What're you doing?
-You don't have a suit, you're not safe.

557
00:38:11,206 --> 00:38:13,458
You don't have a suit,
so you're in as much danger as I am.

558
00:38:13,541 --> 00:38:15,919
-I'm not leaving...
-Donna, let me explain!

559
00:38:16,044 --> 00:38:18,129
Ah, that's how you do it.

560
00:38:18,213 --> 00:38:19,714
SONG: Doctor.

561
00:38:25,678 --> 00:38:26,971
(SCREAMING)

562
00:38:32,644 --> 00:38:34,270
Where did it go?

563
00:38:34,395 --> 00:38:37,357
It's just gone, I looked around,
one shadow, see?

564
00:38:37,440 --> 00:38:39,609
Does that mean we can leave?
I don't want to hang around here.

565
00:38:39,734 --> 00:38:42,695
I don't know why we're still here.
We can leave him, can't we?

566
00:38:42,779 --> 00:38:45,657
-I mean, no offence.
-Shut up, Mr Lux.

567
00:38:45,740 --> 00:38:48,618
Did you feel anything like
an energy transfer? Anything at all?

568
00:38:48,701 --> 00:38:51,162
No, no, but look. It's gone.

569
00:38:51,246 --> 00:38:53,623
Stop there. Stop. Stop. Stop there.
Stop moving.

570
00:38:53,706 --> 00:38:56,960
They're never just gone
and they never give up.

571
00:38:59,504 --> 00:39:02,131
Mmm-mmm. This one's benign.

572
00:39:02,257 --> 00:39:04,592
Hey, who turned out the lights?

573
00:39:04,717 --> 00:39:08,304
-No one, they're fine.
-No, seriously, turn them back on.

574
00:39:08,388 --> 00:39:10,223
They are on.

575
00:39:10,306 --> 00:39:12,267
I can't see a ruddy thing.

576
00:39:12,350 --> 00:39:15,770
-Dave, turn around.
-What's going on?

577
00:39:15,854 --> 00:39:18,773
Why can't I see? Is the power gone?

578
00:39:18,857 --> 00:39:21,401
-Are we safe here?
-Dave, I want you to stay still.

579
00:39:21,484 --> 00:39:23,236
Absolutely still.

580
00:39:23,319 --> 00:39:27,198
Dave, Dave, Dave, can you hear me?
Talk to me, Dave.

581
00:39:28,992 --> 00:39:33,079
-I'm fine. I'm okay, I'm fine.
-I want you to stay still.

582
00:39:33,162 --> 00:39:35,623
-Absolutely still.
-I'm fine.

583
00:39:36,457 --> 00:39:38,543
I'm okay, I'm fine.

584
00:39:40,003 --> 00:39:44,007
I can't... Why can't I? I...

585
00:39:45,341 --> 00:39:48,595
I can't..Why can'tl? I...

586
00:39:50,054 --> 00:39:53,391
I can't..Why can'tl? I...

587
00:39:54,809 --> 00:39:57,061
-He's gone. He's ghosting.
-I can't...Why can't I? I...

588
00:39:57,145 --> 00:39:59,606
Then why is he still standing?

589
00:40:00,523 --> 00:40:02,901
Hey, who turned out the lights?

590
00:40:03,902 --> 00:40:06,905
-Hey, who turned out the lights?
-Doctor, don't.

591
00:40:07,322 --> 00:40:10,742
-Dave, can you hear me?
-Hey, who turned out the lights?

592
00:40:14,662 --> 00:40:16,748
Who turned out the lights?

593
00:40:17,332 --> 00:40:20,335
-Hey, who turned out the lights?
-Excuse me!

594
00:40:21,336 --> 00:40:23,963
Back from it, get back, right back!

595
00:40:29,427 --> 00:40:32,597
-Doesn't move that fast, does it?
-It's a swarm in a suit.

596
00:40:32,680 --> 00:40:34,641
But it's learning.

597
00:40:40,021 --> 00:40:44,275
-What do we do? Where do we go?
-See that wall behind you?

598
00:40:44,359 --> 00:40:45,693
Duck.

599
00:40:46,152 --> 00:40:48,196
Squareness gun!

600
00:40:48,696 --> 00:40:52,992
Everybody out. Go, go, go. Move it.
Move, move.

601
00:40:53,868 --> 00:40:55,662
Move it. Move, move.

602
00:40:56,663 --> 00:40:59,374
-You said not every shadow.
-But any shadow.

603
00:41:02,460 --> 00:41:05,046
-Hey, who turned out the lights?
-SONG: Run.

604
00:41:19,936 --> 00:41:21,646
Sweetie, dinner's ready.

605
00:41:23,231 --> 00:41:25,441
Donna Noble has been saved.

606
00:41:26,901 --> 00:41:28,069
Sweetie?

607
00:41:33,658 --> 00:41:36,244
(DISTANT BUZZING)

608
00:41:52,301 --> 00:41:54,012
Trying to boost the power.

609
00:41:54,095 --> 00:41:56,347
Light doesn't stop them,
but it slows them down.

610
00:41:56,431 --> 00:42:00,935
So, what's the plan? We have a plan?

611
00:42:01,019 --> 00:42:02,520
Your screwdriver.

612
00:42:05,481 --> 00:42:08,109
-Looks exactly like mine.
-Yeah.

613
00:42:08,192 --> 00:42:11,029
-You gave it to me.
-I don't give my screwdriver to anyone.

614
00:42:11,112 --> 00:42:14,198
-I'm not anyone.
-Who are you?

615
00:42:14,824 --> 00:42:18,703
-What's the plan?
- Iteleported Donna back to the Tardis.

616
00:42:18,786 --> 00:42:20,538
If we don't get back there
in under five hours,

617
00:42:20,621 --> 00:42:22,290
Emergency Programme One will activate.

618
00:42:22,373 --> 00:42:24,709
Take her home, yeah.
We need to get a shift on.

619
00:42:24,792 --> 00:42:28,254
She's not there.
I should've received a signal.

620
00:42:28,337 --> 00:42:30,673
The console signals me
if there's a teleport breach.

621
00:42:30,798 --> 00:42:34,385
Maybe the coordinates have slipped.
The equipment here's ancient.

622
00:42:34,469 --> 00:42:37,430
Donna Noble. There's a Donna Noble
somewhere in this library,

623
00:42:37,513 --> 00:42:40,224
do you have the software
to locate her position?

624
00:42:40,308 --> 00:42:43,144
Donna Noble has left the library.

625
00:42:43,227 --> 00:42:45,688
Donna Noble has been saved.

626
00:42:45,938 --> 00:42:49,901
-Donna...
-Donna Noble has left the library.

627
00:42:50,485 --> 00:42:52,236
Donna Noble has been saved.

628
00:42:52,320 --> 00:42:55,073
How can it be Donna?
How's that possible?

629
00:42:55,156 --> 00:42:58,326
Donna Noble has left the library.

630
00:42:58,409 --> 00:43:00,495
Donna Noble has been saved.

631
00:43:00,578 --> 00:43:02,663
-Oh, Donna...
-Donna Noble has...

632
00:43:02,747 --> 00:43:04,499
Hey, who turned out the lights?

633
00:43:04,624 --> 00:43:06,584
-Doctor.
-Donna Noble has been saved.

634
00:43:06,667 --> 00:43:08,002
Hey, who turned out the lights?

635
00:43:08,127 --> 00:43:10,922
Donna Noble has left the library.

636
00:43:11,005 --> 00:43:13,633
-Doctor, we've got to go now!
-Donna Noble has been saved.

637
00:43:13,716 --> 00:43:15,134
Hey, who turned out the lights?

638
00:43:15,218 --> 00:43:17,512
Donna Noble has left the library.

639
00:43:18,763 --> 00:43:21,849
-Donna Noble has been saved.
-Hey, who turned out the lights?

640
00:43:21,933 --> 00:43:25,019
Donna Noble has left the library.

641
00:43:25,103 --> 00:43:27,855
-Donna Noble has been saved.
-Hey, who turned out the lights?

642
00:43:27,980 --> 00:43:30,775
Donna Noble has left the library.

643
00:43:30,900 --> 00:43:33,361
-Donna Noble has been saved.
-Hey, who turned out the lights?

644
00:43:33,444 --> 00:43:35,947
Donna Noble has left the library.

645
00:43:36,030 --> 00:43:37,698
Doctor, what're we gonna do?

646
00:43:37,782 --> 00:43:41,285
-Hey, who turned out the lights?
-Donna Noble has left the library.

647
00:43:41,369 --> 00:43:43,538
Donna Noble has been saved.

648
00:44:17,029 --> 00:44:18,531
I trust that man
to the end of the universe.

649
00:44:18,614 --> 00:44:20,867
-And actually, we've been.
-Who are you?

650
00:44:20,950 --> 00:44:23,452
And then you forgot.

651
00:44:23,828 --> 00:44:27,540
You just killed someone I like,
that is not a safe place to stand.

652
00:44:29,250 --> 00:44:30,585
This planet is gonna crack like an egg.

653
00:44:30,710 --> 00:44:32,795
Daddy! No, Daddy!

654
00:44:33,421 --> 00:44:35,756
-I hate you sometimes.
-I know.

655
00:44:38,718 --> 00:44:39,969
Don't play games with me.

656
00:44:40,052 --> 00:44:41,929
We need to stop this.
We've gotta save CAL.

657
00:44:42,054 --> 00:44:43,306
What is it? What is CAL?

658
00:44:43,431 --> 00:44:45,099
-Spoilers.
-Spoilers.

659
00:44:45,183 --> 00:44:47,059
No, don't tell! You mustn't tell!

